Neuroimaging data#

This notebook presents some useful python libraries to interact with neuroimaging data. Along the way we’ll also learn more about the data structures as well.

BIDS#

BIDS is a data organization scheme to enable easier sharing of neuroimaging datasets. Another advantage of organizing your data according to BIDS is that you can BIDS-apps like fmriprep.

BIDS has a lot of infrastructure built around it. You can check if your data complies with the standard using the Python package pybids.

from bids import BIDSLayout, BIDSValidator
import os

data_dir = '../data/Localizer'
layout = BIDSLayout(data_dir, derivatives=True)
layout

Aside from listing paths or subject identifiers, various other attributes of each BIDSFile can be queried through this python library.

Nibabel#

nibabel is a python library that allows you load and interact with neuroimaging data.

Below we use pybids to get the path for S01’s preprocessed anatomical T1w image.

import nibabel as nib

data = nib.load(layout.get(subject='S01', scope='derivatives', suffix='T1w', return_type='file', extension='nii.gz')[1])

Since the anatomical image does not contain a time-series of BOLD signal, it has 3 dimensions.

data.shape

(193, 229, 193)

We can access the intensity values (/the data) in each voxel using the get_fdata() function. If we are interested in specific coordinates we can subset those from this output.

data.get_fdata()[154, 33, 94]

3528.3837890625

Nifti files contain lots of useful information about the image in their headers. We can access these headers using nibabel.

print(data.header)

Nilearn#

nilearn is a very comprehensive tool, which could be used for most parts of an analysis pipeline. First we’ll look at some its plotting functionality.

nilearn.plotting#

%matplotlib inline

from nilearn.plotting import view_img, plot_glass_brain, plot_anat, plot_epi

Since the image we loaded was a T1w anatomical image we can use the plot_anat function to view it. Note the additional arguments to specify details of the visualization.

plot_anat(data, draw_cross=False, display_mode='z')

<nilearn.plotting.displays._slicers.ZSlicer at 0x1087ac7c0>

We can also make scrollable interactive images. But note that these require more memory so having many of them concurrently active in a single notebook might crash the notebook.

view_img(data, cmap = "twilight")

nilearn.maskers#

Maskers are convenience functions that allow us to work with the data in the 3D images.

If you’re familiar with scikit-learn, nilearn.maskers.NiftiMasker is similar to a scikit-learn transformer. The typical usage is initialization (e.g. nifti_masker = NiftiMasker()) -> fit() -> transform(). Transforming a 4D image results in a samples x features 2D matrix (n_voxels x n_time_points).

Below is an example usage taken from a nilearn tutorial.

from nilearn import datasets

dataset = datasets.fetch_development_fmri(n_subjects=1)
func_filename = dataset.func[0]

# print basic information on the dataset
print(f"First functional nifti image (4D) is at: {func_filename}")

First functional nifti image (4D) is at: /Users/zenkavi/nilearn_data/development_fmri/development_fmri/sub-pixar123_task-pixar_space-MNI152NLin2009cAsym_desc-preproc_bold.nii.gz

 ...done. (2 seconds, 0 min)

from nilearn.maskers import NiftiMasker

# As this is raw movie watching based EPI, the background is noisy and we
# cannot rely on the 'background' masking strategy. We need to use the 'epi'
# one
nifti_masker = NiftiMasker(
    standardize="zscore_sample",
    mask_strategy="epi",
    memory="nilearn_cache",
    memory_level=2,
    smoothing_fwhm=8,
)
nifti_masker.fit(func_filename)
mask_img = nifti_masker.mask_img_

fmri_masked = nifti_masker.transform(func_filename)
# fmri_masked is now a 2D matrix, (n_voxels x n_time_points)

As shown in the tutorial this transformed data can then be used as input into other scikit-learn functions (e.g. ICA).
